Vendored reference data and runner for the `rescm_balanced_gdp` benchmark.

  reference.py        mlsynth's runner: the authors' scmrelax L2RelaxationCV on
                      the balanced-GDP panel (treated = United Kingdom, outcome =
                      year-over-year GDP growth, pre-period ending 2016-06-30,
                      treatment 2016Q3). Reproduces the spec of the authors'
                      GDP_application_2016.ipynb cell-for-cell, then emits the
                      CV-selected tau and the L2 weight vector. Produces the
                      captured bundle. scmrelax's hardcoded MOSEK solver is routed
                      to the open CLARABEL solver (the L2 relaxation is a convex QP
                      with a unique, solver-invariant optimum).

Data
  basedata/balanced_gdp.csv  The authors' quarterly real-GDP panel (58 economies,
                      2002Q4-2024Q2, CEIC), vendored verbatim from the authors'
                      repo (balanced_GDP_data.csv). The two upstream repos ship
                      byte-for-byte identical data (verified equal column-by-column).

Reference
  The reference is Liao-Shi-Zheng's relaxed-balanced synthetic control. It is
  available as BOTH:
    * github.com/YapengZheng/Relaxed_SC   -- the original author code (Yapeng
      Zheng): balanced_GDP_data.csv + GDP_application_2016.ipynb /
      GDP_application_2020.ipynb (the Brexit GDP empirical example).
    * github.com/metricshilab/scmrelax    -- the packaged version of that same
      Relaxed_SC code (the installable `scmrelax` package, used here); its
      docs/ ship the same balanced_GDP_data.csv and notebooks.
  scmrelax hardcodes the commercial MOSEK solver; because the L2 relaxation is a
  plain convex QP with a unique optimum, the runner transparently routes those
  solves to the open CLARABEL solver. The optimum was independently confirmed
  with CLARABEL, ECOS, OSQP and SCS (all agree to solver precision).

Source
  Liao, Wei, Zhentao Shi & Yapeng Zheng (2026), "A Relaxation Approach to
  Synthetic Control" (arXiv 2508.01793). Data and notebook taken from the
  authors' repos above; vendored so the reference run is reproducible offline.
  All credit to the authors. These files produce the captured reference bundle
  only and are not part of the mlsynth library.
